How well did you accomplish them?

Please let me know how well you feel you accomplished your tasks, in a general sense. What do you feel you did the best, and what did you do the least well? What was the hardest part for you? Did your work/understanding/ease improve over the course of the semester?




I accomplished most of the task well. I feel like I did the best on the replication assignment because I was the most personally invested and the assignment had problems which I had to solve. I think the final product is very good, good enough to possibly send to the author. Because of its many replication problems, the replication assignment was also probably the most difficult assignment overall. I did the worst on the function building section of the fourth homework. Although I was able to build a function with many parts, I was still unable to do everything the function was supposed to do. My work definetly improved over the semester, by learning more things I can do with R and how to share my research via github I am more confident in the future of the research. I would not have been able to do the replication project and the module without the things I learned during the class.




How has your understanding of and approach to statistics and project design changed since taking this course?

This may be in relation to previous knowledge, or in relation to future/planned work.





My ability to handle a large amount of code, like that which I will probably have to do for my thesis has greatly improved. The replication assignment was helpful because we essentially did an entire study work of code. I have never handled that big of a coding project before. This makes me feel like I can actualy handle my thesis project. By doing the modules, I also feel like I have a much larger statisitical tool belt which I can apply to future research. In additon, I am able to share the code on github which previously was extremely intimidating to me.





What did you learn from all this?

Please name at least three things you feel you learned in this course.





  1. I learned how to do version control and create html files. I had worked with R prevoiusly, but we only worked with basic scripts and submitted those. I am glad I can now use markdowns and push things to github.

  2. Because we were working through a very complex R cirriculum, I was able to teach basic R to my undergraduate lab much better. I have an incredible grasp on basic ggplot now and am able to point out errors in my students code much better than I could at the beginning. I also know error messages that my undergrads get well and can prescribe a solution based on the error.

  3. Finally, I learned lots of statisical analyses I can apply to future project and the ability to figure out how to use unknown analyses and apply them to my work.





What did your learn about teamwork in this course? How did the readings on teamwork foster this understanding? How did the teamwork experiences?







The teamwork aspect of this course was helpful because it would have been very difficult for everyone individually to figure all things out on their own. Since everyone came from different backgrounds and had different skills, it was important that we shared our knowledge with others and that made it much easier to get things done. Because of my experiences in R troubleshooting I was able to help people fix their code, especially in the beginning. I told my undergraduates many times that the best way to learn R is with other peoples help and it is definitely true.







How did the Peer Commentary process and Group Project relate, if at all, to what you view as your successes or difficulties in this course?







I think the peer commentary was helpful, especially in the difficult assignments, as starting point to communication and collaboration throughout the week. I think it contributed to my success in the assignments. The group project was a good way to apply the skills we learned throughot the course and figure out how to perform our own analysis. This is something I will need to do for research going forward so it is good to get a start now. Lastly, the accumulation of all the group projects was a great way to expand all of our statistical toolbelts and learn how to do new things.







What, if anything, of lasting value do you take away from this experience? If nothing, what would you do differently if you were to start over in this course?







I will continue to use the statistics I learned in this course in my future work and will hopefully always have the modules to refer to. The assignments I did can also serve as resources for myself in the future. If I am ever ask to replicate a study, I can refer to my replication and if I am ever asked to explain a R concept I can refer to the module I created with my group. I will also continue to use Github going forward. By the end of the semester, I had started making it a goal to make my github calendar green (it turns green on a day you commit something so the game is to not miss a day). Hopefully, after a break for the holidays, I will find other things to continue to fill the calendar with green.
